      ESG M&A
   =20
 =20
We  talked yesterday about Carl Icahn=E2=80=99s plans to mount a proxy figh=
t at McDonald=E2=80=99s Corp. over its treatment of pigs. It is a strange s=
ituation. On the one hand, Icahn=E2=80=99s motives seem essentially altruis=
tic and uneconomical: He cares about animal welfare, his daughter worked at=
 the Humane Society and got him involved, he owns only a tiny number of McD=
onald=E2=80=99s shares and isn=E2=80=99t in it for the money. On the other =
hand, Icahn is a billionaire and a ruthless corporate raider with a long hi=
story of investing millions of dollars in scorched-earth proxy fights and w=
inning them. That combination is unusual.But with the higher profile of env=
ironmental, social and governance investing, you would expect to see more s=
tuff=C2=A0like=C2=A0this. There are a lot of rich people who care about ESG=
 issues, proxy-fight expertise can be hired, and there are probably more ca=
ses where mounting a public-company proxy fight is a decent use of a few mi=
llion dollars to achieve some environmental or social aim.=C2=A0On the othe=
r hand, to win a proxy fight, you need other shareholders to vote with you.=
 Lots of shareholders care about ESG these days, so you have the wind at yo=
ur back, but you still need to make a business case to them to have a reali=
stic shot. =E2=80=9CMcDonald=E2=80=99s should treat pigs better to avoid a =
customer backlash that would reduce sales=E2=80=9D is fine, but =E2=80=9CMc=
Donald=E2=80=99s should permanently sacrifice profits for the good of pigs=
=E2=80=9D is not a good pitch to shareholders even if both you and the Blac=
kRock Inc. governance specialist covering McDonald=E2=80=99s happen to beli=
eve it. Fortunately it is a pretty standard form of ESG argument to say =E2=
=80=9Cdoing this thing that is good for the environment will also be good f=
or cash flows in the long run,=E2=80=9D and Engine No. 1 LLC=E2=80=99s  pro=
xy fight at Exxon Mobil Corp. last year=C2=A0shows that those forms of argu=
ment can be used to win a proxy fight.If you have a=C2=A0lot=C2=A0of money,=
 though, you can sort of circumvent this problem. Never mind a proxy fight;=
 do a hostile takeover offer. Find some public company doing a thing you do=
n=E2=80=99t like, buy the company, and stop it doing the thing. The pitch t=
o shareholders is not =E2=80=9Cstopping this thing will make you more money=
,=E2=80=9D but rather =E2=80=9CI will just give you more money =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0I will buy your shares at a premium =E2=80=94=C2=A0and then I will stop =
the company from doing the thing for my own reasons which don=E2=80=99t con=
cern you.=E2=80=9DThis is not really feasible=C2=A0with McDonald=E2=80=99s,=
 which has=C2=A0a $190 billion=C2=A0market capitalization and=C2=A0does lot=
s of things, only some of which Carl Icahn doesn=E2=80=99t like. But you co=
uld imagine someone who made billions of dollars in tech being easily able =
to afford, say, a thermal coal miner, or a gun manufacturer. You buy it, yo=
u shut down the coal mines, you keep the employees on for a few years to pl=
ant trees on the coal mines and=C2=A0retrain to be blockchain engineers.Thi=
s is probably not the best bang for your buck in philanthropy or anything,[=
1] but it might have some positive externalities. Other companies with bad =
ESG records will have to think not just =E2=80=9Cif we continue to have bad=
 ESG records, ESG funds will dump our stock, slightly depressing our stock =
price, and our large index-fund holders will come in every quarter and make=
 sad faces at us,=E2=80=9D but also =E2=80=9Cif we continue to have bad ESG=
 records some tech billionaire will buy us out, fire all the executives and=
 plant flowers in our factories.=E2=80=9D Expanding the toolkit of=C2=A0coe=
rcive=C2=A0ESG strategies =E2=80=94=C2=A0not just asking executives nicely =
to be better at ESG, but firing them if they say no =E2=80=94=C2=A0can be a=
 way to accelerate good ESG behavior in public companies generally, even if=
 you rarely use the coercive tools.Anyway this isn=E2=80=99t really that, b=
ut it=E2=80=99s fascinating:Late last year, as world leaders entered the fi=
nal stages of negotiations for emissions targets they would make at COP26 c=
limate summit in Glasgow, a small team had formed in Australia plotting wha=
t could turn out to be one of the single largest decarbonisation projects t=
he world had yet seen.The team called itself Project Arise =E2=80=93 a part=
nership between the Australian software billionaire Mike Cannon-Brookes and=
 his wife Annie=E2=80=99s private investment vehicle Grok Ventures and Cana=
dian asset manager Brookfield, a corporate behemoth with a track record of =
serious energy and infrastructure investing.Project Arise was secretly asse=
ssing making an offer to buy AGL, the largest Australian power company. Par=
t of its ambitious proposal would be to fast-track the company=E2=80=99s pl=
ans to close its fleet of coal-fired power stations and invest an extraordi=
nary $10-20 billion in projects to replace them, including with wind farms =
and big batteries.For years, Cannon-Brookes, the co-founder of Atlassian an=
d Australia=E2=80=99s third richest person, had made his frustration at Aus=
tralia=E2=80=99s lumbering climate politics and lack of meaningful action a=
bundantly clear. ...Cannon-Brookes has become a prominent investor in renew=
able energy, including plans to develop the world=E2=80=99s largest solar f=
arm in the Northern Territory and link it via an underwater cable to Singap=
ore.In 2021, he started thinking about what more his money could do for the=
 planet. =E2=80=A6The ambitious offer for AGL was lobbed on Saturday. It va=
lued the company at $8 billion, with another $10 billion to $20 billion pro=
mised to bankroll a new fleet of renewable energy including wind farms and =
big batteries that would help replace AGL=E2=80=99s coal-fired power statio=
ns and bring forward their retirement to as early as 2030, 15 years sooner =
than the company=E2=80=99s current plans.The plan here is obviously to earn=
 a financial return; Cannon-Brookes=E2=80=99s motivations might be partly o=
r entirely altruistic but Brookfield is a business. The goal is to buy a po=
lluting power company and accelerate its transition to being a less-polluti=
ng power company that is economically viable for the long term, not to buy =
it and shut it down and write off the $8 billion purchase price.But that is=
 a standard ESG move: Make changes that are good for the environment, and a=
lso make a case that they are good for sustainable long-term shareholder re=
turns. The Exxon proxy fight showed that those sorts of=C2=A0arguments can =
win the support of public shareholders in a proxy fight. Apparently they ca=
n also raise the money=C2=A0for a takeover.
