The problem with collecting tens of millions of dollars as part of a billio=
n-dollar bribery scandal is that your friends and loved ones and enemies an=
d in particular your soon-to-be-exes will notice and demand a cut of your m=
illions and  then where will you be:The bribery trial of ex-Goldman Sachs G=
roup Inc.=C2=A0banker=C2=A0Roger Ng=C2=A0turned tabloid for a while on Tues=
day as Ng=E2=80=99s former boss=C2=A0Tim Leissner testified that a media CE=
O with whom he had an affair blackmailed him into buying her a $10 million =
home.Asked by prosecutor Drew Rolle about his extramarital affairs, Leissne=
r cited several, including one with=C2=A0Rohana Rozhan, former chief execut=
ive officer of media company Astro Malaysia Holdings Bhd. The relationship =
lasted from 2003 to 2013, he told the jury.=C2=A0Rolle asked Leissner wheth=
er he had ever given Rozhan any money he received from his=C2=A01MDB work. =
Leissner said he had =E2=80=94=C2=A0and that he bought her a $10 million ho=
me in London in 2013 after she=E2=80=99d threatened to expose his involveme=
nt with 1MDB.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CMs. Rozhan was very upset that I was ending our=
 relationship to be with my future wife, with Kimora,=E2=80=9D Leissner tes=
tified, referring to his wife=C2=A0Kimora Lee Simmons. =E2=80=9CIf I didn=
=E2=80=99t buy her a house, she would tell the authorities about my involve=
ment in the 1MDB scandal. She was threatening to expose me. At the time, 20=
13, I was very fearful of that.=E2=80=9DYeah well look how that worked out =
for you. Do you think she has to give the house back? (To Malaysia, I mean,=
 not to Leissner.)=C2=A0She is not exactly an innocent good-faith transfere=
e here, if you believe him, which why would you.Leissner=E2=80=99s testimon=
y is fascinating because here you have a very successful investment banker =
who (1) is publicly describing his work, (2) is legally obligated to tell t=
he unvarnished truth (because he has a plea agreement with prosecutors requ=
iring honesty), and (3) actually has=C2=A0 incentives to make it sound extr=
a-bad=C2=A0(because he is cooperating with prosecutors to try to convict Ng=
, and will be rewarded for effective cooperation with a shorter sentence). =
So you end up getting basically the most cynical possible description of in=
vestment banking from someone who did it at a high level.=C2=A0For instance=
, Leissner allegedly worked with a financier named Jho Low to  loot Malaysi=
a=E2=80=99s 1MDB development fund of billions of dollars, with Goldman gett=
ing some $600 million of fees=C2=A0and Leissner himself collecting tens of =
millions of dollars of secret kickbacks. Goldman=E2=80=99s compliance depar=
tment did not want the firm to deal with Low, and for the billion-dollar lo=
oting of 1MDB Leissner helped conceal Low=E2=80=99s involvement from compli=
ance. But for other stuff Leissner  used compliance as an excuse not to do =
thankless work:At the same time, Leissner testified, he sometimes alerted G=
oldman compliance when he decided a deal wouldn=E2=80=99t earn him enough m=
oney to be worth the =E2=80=9Cheadache=E2=80=9D of trying to survive the ba=
nk=E2=80=99s vetting process.=C2=A0One such deal Low proposed involved hiri=
ng Goldman to work on the purchase of a Kazakh gold mine, Leissner told the=
 court. He said Low asked for Leissner=E2=80=99s and Ng=E2=80=99s help even=
 after Goldman had rejected him as a private wealth client because there we=
re concerns about the source of his wealth. Leissner said he went straight =
to compliance.=E2=80=9CIt was going to be painful, and it wasn=E2=80=99t go=
ing to be big enough for us,=E2=80=9D he said.The content of this is =E2=80=
=9Ca criminal tried to hire us to do a deal, and we went through proper com=
pliance channels and said no,=E2=80=9D but you can make that sound bad if y=
ou want to.Disclosure, I used to work at Goldman, though I did not loot any=
 sovereign development funds and keep the money for myself or anything. In =
fact I never did anything illegal at all. But occasionally I would get an=
=C2=A0annoying wheel-spinning project=C2=A0for a client I didn=E2=80=99t kn=
ow much about, and I would entertain some wan hope that compliance would te=
ll me to drop it. =E2=80=9CAh well, compliance said no, what can I do,=E2=
=80=9D I would shrug to the relationship banker, and then head off to enjoy=
 my weekend. This never actually happened to me but it=E2=80=99s nice that =
it did for Leissner.
