   =20
      Comp
   =20
 =20
Here is a slide deck from Litquidity covering its =E2=80=9C2021 Investment =
Banking Compensation Survey.=E2=80=9D (You have to put in an email to read =
it; the results are summarized in the New York Post=C2=A0and eFinancialCare=
ers.) Most of the slides are tables of reported pay (base salary and median=
 bonus) for different levels (first-year analyst through first-year vice pr=
esident and sometimes beyond) in investment banking at the major banks and =
boutiques. First, though, there are two slides on banks=E2=80=99 Seamless d=
inner allowances, which are obviously a major focus for junior bankers ever=
ywhere. They=C2=A0come in three brackets, $25, $30 and $35+. You do not wan=
t to be in the lowest bracket, as Goldman Sachs Group Inc. is. From the dec=
k:An analyst at Goldman Sachs cannot even get a meal from Chipotle at their=
 current dinner allowanceAn increase to $35 will be seen as a significant a=
nd meaningful improvement by junior bankers in their quality of lifeAs bank=
s have record year profits, yet continue to struggle with attrition, while =
requiring working to return to office, this is an easy and tangible improve=
ment for the lives of juniorsIf an analyst eats dinner at the office 365 ni=
ghts a year, going from $25 to $35 will cost the bank at most $3,650. Later=
 in the deck you learn that median second-year analyst compensation at Gold=
man was $220,000. I submit that (1) the analysts can probably afford to pay=
 for their own Seamless tips but (2) Goldman might be better off paying the=
m $4,000 less, increasing the allowance=C2=A0and not getting called out pub=
licly for a stingy dinner allowance? =E2=80=9CGoldman Sachs bankers gripe t=
heir dinner stipends won=E2=80=99t even cover Chipotle,=E2=80=9D is the New=
 York Post headline, which you don=E2=80=99t want.Anyway broadly speaking I=
 guess the point here is that the pay numbers are high? Like, it was a good=
 year to be an investment banker? Busy but lucrative? Seeing it all laid ou=
t like that in tabular format does seem to make investment banking look mor=
e attractive. Sure some 25-year-olds are getting rich in crypto with much l=
ess work than a Centerview associate, but on the other hand =E2=80=9CCenter=
view associate=E2=80=9D is an actual job that you can be hired for and that=
 pays a regular salary, and apparently that salary is=C2=A0$580,000.=C2=A0E=
lsewhere in  Goldman Sachs comp choices:A year ago, the firm was heralding =
Omer Ismail, 42, as its future. Then the Goldman lifer and a deputy, David =
Stark, left to run a banking startup backed by Walmart Inc., drawing the wr=
ath of Goldman=E2=80=99s leader, David Solomon. =E2=80=A6In January, the fi=
rm blocked the duo from cashing out stock bonuses that had vested and been =
taxed going back five years. Those were shares they should=E2=80=99ve been =
able to sell after standard restrictions had just started to lapse.The puni=
shment mimics the clawbacks that came into vogue after the financial crisis=
 to make sure executives can=E2=80=99t profit from malfeasance. Equity awar=
ds to bankers at Goldman typically vest over three years in equal increment=
s. But recipients aren=E2=80=99t allowed to cash out the stock until five y=
ears after the first award, even as they pay taxes on it. The idea is to en=
sure employees=E2=80=99 interests are aligned with the company=E2=80=99s lo=
ng-term health.With Ismail and Stark, the bank refused to release transfer =
restrictions on stock going back to the 2016 pay cycle. Those shares, grant=
ed in 2017, would have just become eligible for cashing out in January. Exe=
cutives at the bank have argued they have the right to confiscate that stoc=
k. The pair have also been banished from company-led alumni events.Disclosu=
re, I left Goldman=C2=A0for Dealbreaker=C2=A0and got to keep my (tiny amoun=
t of) vested but restricted stock.=C2=A0The norm does seem to be that if yo=
u leave, you forfeit your unvested stock[2] but keep your vested-but-restri=
cted stock. Perhaps that will change?=C2=A0As the competition for talent he=
ats up, you can either (1) pay more to employees to get them to stay or (2)=
 take away their money if they leave. Obviously it is cheaper to take the m=
oney away, but I am not sure it actually works in the long run to encourage=
 loyalty?=C2=A0Elsewhere in  banker pay:Promotions normally mean a bigger s=
alary, but when C.S. Venkatakrishnan replaced Jes Staley as chief executive=
 officer of=C2=A0Barclays Plc=C2=A0he took a pay cut.Nah that is how it sho=
uld work. How it should work is that the bank has a CEO, and the CEO is an =
effective manager and gets paid a steady large salary for keeping the bank =
steady, and that salary is constrained by the public-relations needs=C2=A0o=
f being a public company and reporting the salary, and the CEO is rewarded =
not just in money but also in prestige and power. And then somewhere on the=
 trading floor there=E2=80=99s some guy=C2=A0you=E2=80=99ve never heard of =
who makes $1 billion for the bank and keeps $100 million of it for himself.=
 The CEO sits atop the entire bank, which is a portfolio of trades some of =
which will work out and some of which won=E2=80=99t; these trades will offs=
et to some extent, reducing the volatility of her compensation. The people =
on the trading floor make, in effect, one bet each; some of these fail and =
they=E2=80=99re fired, some succeed and they=E2=80=99re paid well, and some=
 of them succeed wildly and they're paid really really well. Or promoted to=
 CEO.
