      WAR
   =20
 =20
A form of story that you sometimes see in finance is:=09Someone creates a s=
tatistic, method, index, etc. to try to measure some complicated reality in=
 the world.=09The statistic, etc., is good, and people start using it to me=
asure that reality.=09A derivatives market grows up where people can bet on=
 the statistic, as a proxy for the complicated reality.=09People try to man=
ipulate the statistic, or get early access to it, or otherwise corrupt it t=
o win their bets.=09Administering the statistic becomes a lot more difficul=
t, expensive and legally perilous than it was at the beginning when someone=
 was just making it up out of abstract curiosity.This is not exactly  the s=
tory of Libor, but it is not exactly=C2=A0not=C2=A0the story of Libor eithe=
r: By the end of Libor, it was so legally fraught (because banks had made s=
o many fake Libor submissions) that the regulators had to push banks to kee=
p=C2=A0measuring=C2=A0Libor even as they were also trying to get rid of Lib=
or.Anyway here is a fun Wall Street Journal story about WAR, wins above rep=
lacement, a form of statistic that people try to use to measure a baseball =
player=E2=80=99s overall value to his team. In baseball=E2=80=99s current l=
abor dispute, there is a proposal to pay some players in part based on thei=
r WAR, perhaps as measured by some of the websites that develop and track t=
he measure. The websites don=E2=80=99t like it:When the news leaked last mo=
nth, the response from the analytics community was swift. Baseball-Referenc=
e president Sean Forman tweeted he was =E2=80=9Cnot really interested=E2=80=
=9D in his company=E2=80=99s WAR being part of player compensation. Meg Row=
ley, FanGraphs=E2=80=99 managing editor, posted, =E2=80=9CUsing a public-fa=
cing value metric for player compensation isn=E2=80=99t the best idea.=E2=
=80=9D Russell Carleton of Baseball Prospectus, another site with a version=
 of WAR, =C2=A0called it a =E2=80=9Cterrible idea.=E2=80=9D=E2=80=9CIf MLB =
and the union were to say, =E2=80=98Yeah, we=E2=80=99re going to take the v=
alues off the public sites and use them,=E2=80=99 that would be problematic=
,=E2=80=9D said David Appelman, FanGraphs=E2=80=99 founder. =E2=80=9CThat p=
uts a lot of pressure on us.=E2=80=9D ...As researchers uncover better unde=
rstandings of how to evaluate player performance, WAR is refined to reflect=
 those breakthroughs. For example, how to weigh and evaluate defense is con=
stantly evolving. The same goes for measuring the impact of issues such as =
specific ballparks, catchers=E2=80=99 =E2=80=9Cframing=E2=80=9D of pitches =
and the increased reliance on relief pitchers versus traditional starters, =
among many other areas of the game.=C2=A0Sometimes, WAR is adjusted retroac=
tively to reflect those changes, raising obvious questions: What happens, f=
or instance, if a player=E2=80=99s WAR falls short of qualifying for a bonu=
s payment, only for it to increase a year later?=C2=A0=E2=80=9CI would shud=
der to think, are we going to get sued by somebody for something because of=
 that, if we=E2=80=99re literally costing somebody a million dollars by mak=
ing that change?=E2=80=9D Forman said in an interview. =E2=80=9CI can imagi=
ne circumstances where people get pretty angry with us.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
