   =20
      Market structure
   =20
 =20
We  talked yesterday about the market structure of the market for sterling-=
based inflation products. Specifically, that structure consists of a handfu=
l of traders at big banks, and =E2=80=9Clast summer, a handful of job moves=
 in London had an impact on market liquidity.=E2=80=9D I asked readers: =E2=
=80=9CCan you design a trading strategy to take advantage of this dynamic?=
=E2=80=9D I proposed a dumb one: Hire one bank=E2=80=99s trader, set off a =
daisy chain of hirings, buy a bunch of inflation-linked bonds from the rand=
om trainees covering the desks while everyone is on gardening leave, push u=
p the price while you do so, and then sell your bonds at a profit into a li=
quid market when they get back from leave. A reader emailed to dismiss=C2=
=A0my idea (really, you get long for three months?)=C2=A0and proposed a muc=
h better one:A strategy that is more likely to work is to play market maker=
s against each other. E.g., hit the bid of one trainee trader and then cove=
r your short by lifting the offer of another trainee trader as the market g=
oes your way because the first trainee has been unloading the risk. Rinse a=
nd repeat until everyone is back from gardening leave.Note that this strate=
gy will hurt your relationship with the market maker banks if found out and=
 is considered bad behavior.Just hire one inflation trader, set off the dai=
sy chain of gardening leaves, and then ask for markets from the six trainee=
s filling in on the six inflation desks. The markets will be all over the p=
lace because no one knows anything, so you can make a bunch of money from t=
he illiquidity you created through personnel changes.
