      NFT Stuff
   =20
 =20
Sure:Hundreds of Salesforce employees globally are rebelling against plans =
by the U.S. enterprise software giant to enter the non-fungible token (NFT)=
 market, according to internal documents seen by the Thomson Reuters Founda=
tion.Salesforce told employees last week it was exploring a series of NFT i=
nitiatives, including an "NFT Cloud" which could help companies around the =
world create and sell NFTs - a kind of digital asset often linked to an ima=
ge or piece of artwork, which is usually bought with cryptocurrencies.More =
than 400 employees have signed on to an open letter which was penned after =
the company's announcement, and is being shared in internal messaging chann=
els.It is addressed to Salesforce's co-CEOs, and raises concerns about the =
environmental and economic impact of NFTs, calling them "unregulated, highl=
y speculative financial assets."Okay I actually have an idea to make everyo=
ne happy. You, Salesforce.com Inc., run a company that essentially sells da=
tabases on cloud servers. =E2=80=9CWe deliver a single source of truth,=E2=
=80=9D you actually say in your annual report. An NFT is an entry in a data=
base. These days the stereotypical NFT=C2=A0is an entry in a particular kin=
d of database =E2=80=94=C2=A0a proof-of-work blockchain =E2=80=94=C2=A0that=
 requires enormous amounts of energy to maintain. But if you are building y=
our own =E2=80=9CNFT Cloud=E2=80=9D you can make it any sort of database yo=
u want. Make it a CSV file!=C2=A0Be the single source of truth! The disadva=
ntage of that is that it is not decentralized and permissionless and immuta=
ble and =E2=80=9Ccrypto.=E2=80=9D The advantages are:=09Minimal environment=
al cost,=09Faster, and=09It is not decentralized and permissionless and imm=
utable and crypto: Instead of owning NFTs =E2=80=9Con the blockchain,=E2=80=
=9D people can own them =E2=80=9Cat Salesforce.=E2=80=9D Salesforce can be =
the single source of truth about who owns the NFT. Seems good for business?=
Is this stupid? Of course. But compared to what.By the way, I gather that a=
 lot of games companies are also getting pushback from employees and custom=
ers about their NFT initiatives, and I am available to consult for them too=
:Game company chief executive officer: We want to build a way for players t=
o buy little hats for their characters in our game.Me: Okay what you do is =
you program the game to have a hat store.CEO: But we want them to be able t=
o put the hats on their characters in our other games.Me: Okay so you shoul=
d build a centralized hat store and keep track of which players own hats, a=
nd then let them wear the hats in all the games.CEO: But we want them to be=
 able to put the hats on their characters in other games built by=C2=A0othe=
r=C2=A0companies.Me: No you don=E2=80=99t?=C2=A0CEO: Oh, right, why would w=
e want that.Me: Problem solved, huh?CEO: Well we do want our players to be =
able to make huge speculative profits reselling the hats to each other in t=
he middle of an enormous boom in speculative computer-game-hat trading.Me:=
=C2=A0[looks at CEO sternly]CEO: I don=E2=80=99t like it either but you you=
rself are always writing that  companies should embrace memes and talk abou=
t NFTs.=C2=A0Me: That's diff=E2=80=94=C2=A0CEO: Look I am a simple game des=
igner, I just want to make fun video games, but the reality is that the=C2=
=A0market is clamoring for=C2=A0transferable cryptographically protected ha=
ts for video game characters and I am in a unique position to provide those=
 hats at a low cost. I have a fiduciary responsibility to my shareholders a=
nd frankly I=E2=80=99d be a fool not to rush into selling NFTs,=C2=A0even i=
f it=E2=80=99s stupid.Me: =E2=80=A6CEO: This imaginary dialogue did not go =
how you expected did it?
